        <article>
          <header class="note-header">
            <div>Note # 202506160520</div>
            <h2>The Nature of Knowledge Networks</h2>
          </header>
          <div class="note-body">
            <p>
              Knowledge is not a collection of isolated facts, but rather an
              interconnected web of relationships and associations. Each piece
              of information gains meaning through its connections to other
              concepts.
            </p>
            <p>
              In the context of digital note-taking systems, this principle
              becomes particularly relevant. The Zettelkasten method, developed
              by sociologist Niklas Luhmann, demonstrates how individual notes
              can form a complex network of ideas that transcends linear
              thinking.
            </p>
            <!-- <p>
              The key insight is that knowledge emerges from the relationships
              between ideas, not from the ideas themselves. This is why linking
              and cross-referencing become essential tools in any serious
              knowledge management system.
            </p>
            <p>
              When we create connections between disparate concepts, we enable
              serendipitous discoveries and novel insights that would be
              impossible in a purely hierarchical system.
            </p> -->
